{"title_page": "S. David Freeman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = S. David Freeman\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1926|1|14|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chattanooga]], [[Tennessee]], United States\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2020|5|12|1926|1|14|mf=yes}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Georgia Tech]]<br>[[University of Tennessee College of Law]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])}}\n}}\n\n'''S. David Freeman''' (January 14, 1926 \u2013 May 12, 2020) was an American engineer, attorney, and author, who had many key roles in energy policy.\n\n==Early life==\nFreeman was born on January 14, 1926, in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]],<ref>http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=7827</ref> as the son of a shopkeeper. He received a degree in electrical engineering from [[Georgia Tech]].<ref name=\":0\" />  After working for five years with the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] (TVA), he went on to study law at the [[University of Tennessee]], obtaining a [[Juris Doctor]] from that institution.  He subsequently went back to work for the TVA, this time as an attorney.<ref name=LAT>{{cite news|title=S. David Freeman, public power chief and energy advisor, dies at 94|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-05-13/s-david-freeman-public-power-chief-and-energy-adviser-dies-at-94|first=Matthew|last=Ormseth|date=May 13, 2020|accessdate=January 3, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFreeman was appointed to energy committees by President Lyndon Johnson in 1967<ref name=\"renewables100.org\">{{cite web | url=http://www.renewables100.org/en/about-us/board-of-advisors/s-david-freeman/ | title=S. David Freeman: Renewables 100 Policy Institute |date= |access-date=2019-02-14 |author= |quote= }}</ref> and worked in the EPA during Nixon's presidency.<ref name=\"allelectricamerica.com\">{{cite web | url=https://allelectricamerica.com/biodave/ | title=S. David Freeman - |date= |access-date=2019-02-14 |author= |quote= }}</ref>  After President [[Jimmy Carter]] appointed him to head the TVA board in 1977, Freeman changed the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] (TVA) focus from growth to conservation. Freeman decided to stop construction on several nuclear projects that may have contributed to several rate increases with TVA.  {{As of|2020}}, TVA\u2019s generation portfolio is 39% nuclear, 19% coal, 26% natural gas, 11% hydro, 3% wind and solar, and 1% energy efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|title=TVA at a Glance|url=https://www.tva.com/About-TVA/TVA-at-a-Glance|first=Matthew|last=Ormseth|date=May 13, 2020|accessdate=January 3, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = Technology and Transformation in the American Electric Utility Industry | author = Richard F. Hirsh | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2003 | isbn = 0-521-52471-7 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=N8sqNGiMOskC&pg=PA156&ots=OCX27nef8B&dq=%22S+David+Freeman%22+carter&as_brr=3&sig=EP55h8rgYeBIDwjXlxyfknFhAEk#PPA156,M1 }}</ref> He also headed other major energy organizations, including the [[New York Power Authority]] and the [[Los Angeles Department of Water and Power]] (LADWP); he was in charge of the latter from 1997 to 2001.<ref name=LAT/>\n\n==Death==\nFreeman died on May 12, 2020, after having a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at a hospital outside of [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title=S. David Freeman, green energy pioneer and former SMUD chief, dies at 94|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/obituaries/article242692871.html|last=Kasler|first=Dale|date=May 12, 2020|website=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=LAT/>  He was 94, and was hospitalized a week before his death.  News of his death was first announced by his daughter, Anita Hopkins.<ref name=LAT/>\n\n==SMUD==\nFreeman has been termed an \"eco-pioneer\" for his environmentally-oriented leadership of the [[Sacramento Municipal Utility District]] (SMUD).<ref>{{cite book | title = Eco-Pioneers: Practical Visionaries Solving Today's Environmental Problems | author = Steve Lerner | publisher = MIT Press | year = 1998 | isbn = 0-262-62124-X | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XCUXig07qcgC&pg=PA91&ots=CbsrWfVJoG&dq=%22S+David+Freeman%22&as_brr=3&sig=AptWB2veLFLjcbVxofmRhPRKmwM }}</ref> Freeman became general manager of the Sacramento Municipal Utility District in 1990. He has said that SMUD was an embarrassment at that time, and the district was \"reeling from two decades of rate hikes, construction cost overruns, operating failures, equipment outages, worker injuries, poor morale and management scandals\". Freeman left SMUD in 1994 and as of 2012, SMUD is considered a model of efficiency, service and innovation. The turnaround began in 1989 when the people of [[Sacramento]] voted to close the [[Rancho Seco Nuclear Generating Station]].<ref name=free12>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacbee.com/2012/06/02/4532500/time-has-come-for-california-to.html#storylink=cpy |title=Viewpoints: Time has come for California to embrace a nuclear-free future |author=S. David Freeman |date=Jun 2, 2012  |work=Sacramento Bee }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Freeman, since opening in 1971, Rancho Seco had \"suffered dozens of emergencies, shutdowns, releases of radioactive material and accidents\". Freed of this costly, unreliable and dangerous nuclear power station, SMUD went on to earn a worldwide reputation for its affordable, clean, [[renewable energy]] programs.<ref name=free12/> The largest power source for Sacramento is the 500 MW [[Cosumnes, Sacramento County|Cosumnes]] gas plant.[https://www.smud.org/en/Corporate/Environmental-Leadership/Power-Sources]\n\n==Books==\nFreeman has authored several books, including ''Energy: The New Era'' (1974), ''Winning Our Energy Independence'' (2007), An ''All-Electric America: A Climate Solution and the Hopeful Future (2016)'' and an autobiography, ''The Green Cowboy: An Energetic Life'' (2016). Other books that contain his works include ''Oral history of the Tennessee Valley Authority: Interview with S. David Freeman, March 30, 1984'' and ''Speeches by S. David Freeman'' (1997).\n\nIn ''Winning Our Energy Independence'', he wrote that we have the [[renewable energy]] we need to [[wikt:wean|wean]] ourselves from the Three Poisons: [[United States energy independence|foreign oil]], [[dirty coal]] and [[Anti-nuclear movement|dangerous nuclear power]].\n\n{{Cquote|I say this based on my experience as the former head of the [[Tennessee Valley Authority|TVA]], which bought and burned more than 30 million tons of coal a year. I was deeply involved in the strip mining, underground mining, trucking, and most importantly, the burning of huge quantities of coal. No one who has been deeply involved with coal can rightfully say it is clean.|source=S. David Freeman in [https://archive.org/details/winningourenergy00free/page/39 ''Winning Our Energy Independence: An Energy Insider Shows How''] (2007), p. 39, {{ISBN|1423611640}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://globetrotter.berkeley.edu/people3/Freeman/freeman-con0.html Conversation with S. David Freeman]\n* [https://www.texastribune.org/2011/12/06/s-david-freeman-tt-interview/ Interview with S. David Freeman]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freeman, S. David}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with renewable energy]]\n[[Category:People associated with nuclear power]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Sacramento Municipal Utility District]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee College of Law alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = S. David Freeman\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1926|1|14|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chattanooga]], [[Tennessee]], United States\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2020|5|12|1926|1|14|mf=yes}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Georgia Tech]]<br>[[University of Tennessee College of Law] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])}}\n}}\n\n'''S. David Freeman''' (January 14, 1926 \u2013 May 12, 2020) was an American engineer, attorney, and author, who had many key roles in energy policy.\n\n==Early life==\nFreeman was born on January 14, 1926, in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]],<ref>http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=7827</ref> as the son of a shopkeeper. He received a degree in electrical engineering from [[Georgia Tech]].<ref name=\":0\" />  After working for five years with the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] (TVA), he went on to study law at the [[University of Tennessee]], obtaining a [[Juris Doctor]] from that institution.  He subsequently went back to work for the TVA, this time as an attorney.<ref name=LAT>{{cite news|title=S. David Freeman, public power chief and energy advisor, dies at 94|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-05-13/s-david-freeman-public-power-chief-and-energy-adviser-dies-at-94|first=Matthew|last=Ormseth|date=May 13, 2020|accessdate=January 3, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFreeman was appointed to energy committees by President Lyndon Johnson in 1967<ref name=\"renewables100.org\">{{cite web | url=http://www.renewables100.org/en/about-us/board-of-advisors/s-david-freeman/ | title=S. David Freeman: Renewables 100 Policy Institute |date= |access-date=2019-02-14 |author= |quote= }}</ref> and worked in the EPA during Nixon's presidency.<ref name=\"allelectricamerica.com\">{{cite web | url=https://allelectricamerica.com/biodave/ | title=S. David Freeman - |date= |access-date=2019-02-14 |author= |quote= }}</ref>  After President [[Jimmy Carter]] appointed him to head the TVA board in 1977, Freeman changed the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] (TVA) focus from growth to conservation. Freeman decided to stop construction on several nuclear projects that may have contributed to several rate increases with TVA.  {{As of|2020}}, TVA\u2019s generation portfolio is 39% nuclear, 19% coal, 26% natural gas, 11% hydro, 3% wind and solar, and 1% energy efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|title=TVA at a Glance|url=https://www.tva.com/About-TVA/TVA-at-a-Glance|first=Matthew|last=Ormseth|date=May 13, 2020|accessdate=January 3, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = Technology and Transformation in the American Electric Utility Industry | author = Richard F. Hirsh | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2003 | isbn = 0-521-52471-7 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=N8sqNGiMOskC&pg=PA156&ots=OCX27nef8B&dq=%22S+David+Freeman%22+carter&as_brr=3&sig=EP55h8rgYeBIDwjXlxyfknFhAEk#PPA156,M1 }}</ref> He also headed other major energy organizations, including the [[New York Power Authority]] and the [[Los Angeles Department of Water and Power]] (LADWP); he was in charge of the latter from 1997 to 2001.<ref name=LAT/>\n\n==Death==\nFreeman died on May 12, 2020, after having a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at a hospital outside of [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title=S. David Freeman, green energy pioneer and former SMUD chief, dies at 94|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/obituaries/article242692871.html|last=Kasler|first=Dale|date=May 12, 2020|website=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=LAT/>  He was 94, and was hospitalized a week before his death.  News of his death was first announced by his daughter, Anita Hopkins.<ref name=LAT/>\n\n==SMUD==\nFreeman has been termed an \"eco-pioneer\" for his environmentally-oriented leadership of the [[Sacramento Municipal Utility District]] (SMUD).<ref>{{cite book | title = Eco-Pioneers: Practical Visionaries Solving Today's Environmental Problems | author = Steve Lerner | publisher = MIT Press | year = 1998 | isbn = 0-262-62124-X | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XCUXig07qcgC&pg=PA91&ots=CbsrWfVJoG&dq=%22S+David+Freeman%22&as_brr=3&sig=AptWB2veLFLjcbVxofmRhPRKmwM }}</ref> Freeman became general manager of the Sacramento Municipal Utility District in 1990. He has said that SMUD was an embarrassment at that time, and the district was \"reeling from two decades of rate hikes, construction cost overruns, operating failures, equipment outages, worker injuries, poor morale and management scandals\". Freeman left SMUD in 1994 and as of 2012, SMUD is considered a model of efficiency, service and innovation. The turnaround began in 1989 when the people of [[Sacramento]] voted to close the [[Rancho Seco Nuclear Generating Station]].<ref name=free12>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacbee.com/2012/06/02/4532500/time-has-come-for-california-to.html#storylink=cpy |title=Viewpoints: Time has come for California to embrace a nuclear-free future |author=S. David Freeman |date=Jun 2, 2012  |work=Sacramento Bee }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Freeman, since opening in 1971, Rancho Seco had \"suffered dozens of emergencies, shutdowns, releases of radioactive material and accidents\". Freed of this costly, unreliable and dangerous nuclear power station, SMUD went on to earn a worldwide reputation for its affordable, clean, [[renewable energy]] programs.<ref name=free12/> The largest power source for Sacramento is the 500 MW [[Cosumnes, Sacramento County|Cosumnes]] gas plant.[https://www.smud.org/en/Corporate/Environmental-Leadership/Power-Sources]\n\n==Books==\nFreeman has authored several books, including ''Energy: The New Era'' (1974), ''Winning Our Energy Independence'' (2007), An ''All-Electric America: A Climate Solution and the Hopeful Future (2016)'' and an autobiography, ''The Green Cowboy: An Energetic Life'' (2016). Other books that contain his works include ''Oral history of the Tennessee Valley Authority: Interview with S. David Freeman, March 30, 1984'' and ''Speeches by S. David Freeman'' (1997).\n\nIn ''Winning Our Energy Independence'', he wrote that we have the [[renewable energy]] we need to [[wikt:wean|wean]] ourselves from the Three Poisons: [[United States energy independence|foreign oil]], [[dirty coal]] and [[Anti-nuclear movement|dangerous nuclear power]].\n\n{{Cquote|I say this based on my experience as the former head of the [[Tennessee Valley Authority|TVA]], which bought and burned more than 30 million tons of coal a year. I was deeply involved in the strip mining, underground mining, trucking, and most importantly, the burning of huge quantities of coal. No one who has been deeply involved with coal can rightfully say it is clean.|source=S. David Freeman in [https://archive.org/details/winningourenergy00free/page/39 ''Winning Our Energy Independence: An Energy Insider Shows How''] (2007), p. 39, {{ISBN|1423611640}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://globetrotter.berkeley.edu/people3/Freeman/freeman-con0.html Conversation with S. David Freeman]\n* [https://www.texastribune.org/2011/12/06/s-david-freeman-tt-interview/ Interview with S. David Freeman]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freeman, S. David}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with renewable energy]]\n[[Category:People associated with nuclear power]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Sacramento Municipal Utility District]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee College of Law alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Bloom6132", "label": "safe", "comment": "oops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S._David_Freeman"}
